defaultIntegration of disability issues within DFID’s sector programmes (for example in health, education, sadefaultnitation, livelihoods, and empowerment) and its humanitarian workdefault&#xa0;default3.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is a strong link between disability and multi-dimensional poverty
default. It is not lack of funds alone but a lack of inclusion in important areas such as education, health services and soc
defaultial participation, as well as compounding factors such as gender, age and geographical location, that limit the opportunities for disabled people to overcome poverty. Research from the Leonard Cheshire Disability Inclusive Development Centre has recently t
defaultermed this the ‘Disability and Development Gap’
default: disabled people who are not included in development efforts fall increasingly further behind non-disabled members of their communities as development efforts increase. 
