defaultInclusive educationdefault&#xa0;default3.18
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThrough our
default inclusive education projects across
default Africa and Asia
default,
default 
defaultLeonard Cheshire Disability has
default supported over 10,000 children with disabilities to go to school.
default 
defaultOur
default inclusive education work in
default Bangladesh, India and Pakistan, s
defaultupported by Big Lottery Fund
default,
default 
defaultwas recognised 
defaultin 
default‘
defaultBest Practices 
defaultfor 
defaultIncluding Persons 
defaultwith 
defaultDisabilities 
defaultin 
defaultAll Aspects 
defaultof 
defaultDe
defaultvelopment Efforts’
default published by UN in April 2011. The project 
defaultsupported children with disabilities to access mainstream primary edu
defaultcation
default and s
defaultupported them to continue their
default education
default.
default 
defaultOver 3,000 teachers were trained on accommodating children with disab
defaultilities in their classes. Preparatory classes for children with disabilities were organised prior to enrolment into mainstream schools, and an effective home-based education system was designed for areas where the terrain made it hard for children with hig
defaulth support needs to get to school. The project worked closely with schools to make them accessible; and with government officials to ensure that children with disabilities received any government entitlements
default due to them
default. The 
defaultproject also undertook advocacy and policy work, including the formation of parents groups and child-to-child clubs for children with and without disabilities to support meaningful inclusion. In total, over 2,700 children were successfully enrolled in thei
defaultr local primary schools. The project had a significant impact on changing attitudes towards disabled children’s rights to education; there are now more children with disabilities in local primary schools in 
defaultthe project locations
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultLivelihoodsdefault&#xa0;default3.19
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLeonard Che
defaultshire Disability’s Livelihoods Resource Centres (LRCs) in Asia 
defaultand 
defaultAfrica 
default(supported by
default funders including
default Accenture and the European Union
default respectively
default) 
defaulthave been selected by the Zero Project
default as an example of ‘Innovative Practice’ relating to persons with
default disabilities and employment. LRCs act as ‘one-stop-shops’ for disabled people seeking employment, providing 
defaultskills 
defaulttraining, career guidance and links between employees and employers. There are now 22 LRCs in 9 countries across Asia and Africa
default. We have su
defaultpported over 10,000 adults with disabilities into paid or self-employment, and provided training for nearly 50,000
default. LRCs are unique in providing the full range of support that disabled people need when seeking employment or 
defaultstarting their own enterprise
default. L
defaultCD partner
defaults
default with mainstream training institutions, ensuring disabled people get recognised qualifications. The training is also tailored to meet the needs of local employment markets, as well as people’s own interests and talents. Training provision in “so
defaultft skills” (including confidence building, decision making, and critical thinking) also supports the project’s success. In order to support self-employment, the microfinance model used by LRCs includes savings and insurance, known to be an effective povert
defaulty reduction tool.
